const a = [
  {"id":3748,"text":"Concurrent administration of quinidine and digoxin results in drug-drug interaction. How does quinidine interact with digoxin?","explanation":null,"reference":"Bigger JT, Leahey EB. Quinidine and digoxin. An important interaction. Drugs. Published September 1982. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/6751790","responses":[{"text":"Antagonized the effect of digoxin on the A-V node","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased the absorption of digoxin in GIT","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Synergistic effect on myocardium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased serum concentration of digoxin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibits the metabolism of digoxin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4049,"text":"Lidocaine, as an antiarrhythmic, produces what effect?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 252.","responses":[{"text":"Reduced action potential duration","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased contractility","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased action potential duration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased PR interval","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reduced abnormal automaticity","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10392,"text":"Which of the following is incorrect regarding a stab wound?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 200, 201.","responses":[{"text":"It may occur with a knife","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"In this injury bruising around the opening of the wound is seen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It results from piercing with a pointed weapon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Its greatest dimension is depth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is a wedge shaped opening wound","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10401,"text":"Which of the following is correct regarding age and color of a bruise?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 193.","responses":[{"text":"Green on day 2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Depends on size and swelling","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blue on day 4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal at 1 week","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Yellow on day 7-12","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12498,"text":"An industrialist asks a public health specialist about the measures he can take to control and prevent heart disease among employees. The public health specialist advises on the modifiable risk factors that can be addressed to lower the risk of cardiovascular diseases. Which one of the following options illustrates the modifiable risk factor that the industrialist can focus on?","explanation":"**Effective diabetes management** can significantly reduce cardiovascular risk as diabetes is a **modifiable risk factor**. Workplace programs can be implemented to educate employees about diabetes control, offer regular screening, and even provide lifestyle modification options like diet plans and exercise routines.\r\n\r\nEthnicity, family history, age, and gender are non-modifiable risk factors for heart disease and cannot be changed through interventions. Therefore, focusing on diabetes management would be a feasible and impactful approach.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 492.","responses":[{"text":"Ethnicity of employees","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gender of employees","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Family history of employees","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Age of employees","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetes management of employees","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12505,"text":"A patient receiving a class I antiarrhythmic agent on a long-term basis complains of fatigue, low-grade fever, and joint pain suggestive of systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE). The patient is most likely using which of the following antiarrhythmic drugs?","explanation":"The patient is most likely using **procainamide**, a class IA antiarrhythmic agent. Procainamide is known to cause **drug-induced lupus erythematosus**, which can present with symptoms such as fatigue, low-grade fever, and joint pain, mimicking systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE).\r\n\r\nQuinidine is also a class IA antiarrhythmic but is not commonly associated with drug-induced lupus. Propranolol is a beta-blocker, not a class I antiarrhythmic. Lidocaine is a class IB antiarrhythmic primarily used for ventricular arrhythmias and is not associated with drug-induced lupus. Flecainide is class IC antiarrhythmic used for supraventricular arrhythmias and ventricular tachycardia but is also not known to induce lupus-like symptoms.","reference":"Katzung BG, ed. Basic \u0026 Clinical Pharmacology. 14th ed. McGraw Hill; 2018: 238.","responses":[{"text":"Quinidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lidocaine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Procainamide","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Flecainide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Propranolol","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12524,"text":"An elderly patient with a history of heart disease is brought to the emergency room with difficulty breathing. Examination reveals that she has pulmonary edema. Which treatment is indicated using the most potent diuretic?","explanation":"**Furosemide** is the most potent diuretic among the options and is the treatment of choice for **acute pulmonary edema**. \r\n\r\nAcetazolamide is a carbonic anhydrase inhibitor and not potent enough for treating acute conditions. Spironolactone is a potassium-sparing diuretic, which is also weaker and not suitable for immediate management of acute pulmonary edema. Chlorthalidone and hydrochlorothiazide are thiazide diuretics, which are less potent than loop diuretics like furosemide and not ideal for rapid symptom relief in cases of acute pulmonary edema.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 222.","responses":[{"text":"Acetazolamide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydrochlorothiazide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chlorthalidone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Furosemide","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Spironolactone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12737,"text":"You are evaluating a patient with rheumatic fever. He had carditis at diagnosis but no residual valvular disease at discharge. How long will you advise for secondary prophylaxis?","explanation":"According to the American Heart Association (AHA) guidelines, secondary prophylaxis with antibiotics for a patient who had rheumatic fever with carditis but no residual valvular disease should continue for **10 years or until the patient is 21 years of age**, whichever is longer.\r\n\r\nShorter durations of prophylaxis may not provide adequate protection against recurrent attacks of rheumatic fever and potential cardiac involvement.","reference":"Cardiology module; Pediatrics lecture slides; Topic: Rheumatic fever; Sub-topic: Duration of prophylaxis for people who have had acute rheumatic fever.","responses":[{"text":"No need of prophylaxis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"10 years or till 21 years of age whichever is longer","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"10 years or till 40 years of age whichever is longer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2 years or till 21 years of age whichever is longer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"5 years or till 21 years of age whichever is longer","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13312,"text":"Which of the following is incorrect for an incised wound?","explanation":"An **incised wound** is a cut that is longer than it is deep, usually resulting from a sharp-edged object such as a knife, razor, or glass.\r\n\r\nDue to the sharp nature of the weapon or object causing an incised wound, the **edges of the wound are usually clean** and straight, as opposed to the more ragged or irregular edges seen in lacerations or other wound types.\r\n\r\nWhile many incised wounds can be painful due to damage to the skin and underlying tissues, the level of pain experienced can vary depending on factors like the location of the wound, depth, individual pain tolerance, and whether or not any nerves were affected. For instance, wounds that are superficial or that do not involve many nerve endings might not be painful.\r\n\r\nIncised wounds can lead to significant blood loss because of their typically clean and straight nature, which does not encourage immediate blood clotting as might be seen with more jagged wounds.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 198.","responses":[{"text":"It is always caused by a sharp weapon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It Is always painful","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bleeds profusely","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The maximum measurement of an incised wound is its length","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A wound with clean edges","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":17425,"text":"Which antihypertensive can cause rebound hypertension on sudden discontinuation?","explanation":"**Clonidine** is the antihypertensive medication that can cause **rebound hypertension** upon sudden discontinuation. This is because clonidine is a centrally acting alpha-2 adrenergic agonist that reduces sympathetic outflow, leading to lower blood pressure. Sudden withdrawal of the drug can lead to a **sudden increase in sympathetic activity**, resulting in a rapid and potentially dangerous increase in blood pressure.\r\n\r\nLosartan is an angiotensin II receptor blocker and generally does not cause rebound hypertension upon discontinuation. Chlorothiazide is a diuretic, and while sudden discontinuation might lead to a return of hypertension, it is generally not associated with rebound hypertension. Prazosin, an alpha-1 receptor blocker, also is not generally associated with rebound hypertension upon discontinuation.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 84.","responses":[{"text":"Prazosin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chlorothiazide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Losartan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clonidine","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":18019,"text":"An elderly person with a known history of hypertension presents to the clinic. He informs that he has been taking 50 mg hydrochlorothiazide for a while but it no longer helps in reducing blood pressure. He is given another medicine and a spontaneous fall in systolic blood pressure is seen. What is the medication?","explanation":null,"reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 513-514.","responses":[{"text":"Captopril","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atenolol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Losartan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alpha methyldopa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amlodipine","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":18775,"text":"Six months after starting atorvastatin, a patient's total cholesterol and LDL cholesterol\r\nconcentrations remain above normal and he continues to have anginal attacks despite good\r\nadherence to his anti-anginal medications. His physician decides to add niacin.  Which of the following is the major recognized mechanism of action of niacin?","explanation":"Niacin, also known as vitamin B3, is an important medication for managing dyslipidemia, specifically high levels of triglycerides and LDL cholesterol. It primarily works by **inhibiting the liver's production and secretion of VLDL,** which is a precursor to LDL cholesterol. By reducing VLDL levels, niacin indirectly lowers LDL cholesterol levels.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, niacin has some other effects on lipid metabolism, such as increasing the activity of lipoprotein lipase, an enzyme that hydrolyzes triglycerides in circulating lipoproteins. This action further contributes to the reduction of triglyceride levels.\r\n\r\nNiacin also has a modest impact on raising HDL (High-Density Lipoprotein) cholesterol levels, which is considered a favorable effect on cardiovascular health.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 13th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2021: 302, 306.","responses":[{"text":"Decreased secretion of VLDL by the liver","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased endocytosis of HDL by the liver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased lipid synthesis in adipose tissue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased lipid hydrolysis by lipoprotein lipase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased oxidation of lipids in endothelial cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18782,"text":"In which of the following conditions is mid-diastolic murmur heard at the apex?","explanation":"**Mitral stenosis** is a heart valve disorder characterized by the narrowing of the mitral valve, which separates the left atrium from the left ventricle. In this condition, the narrowed valve restricts the flow of blood from the left atrium into the left ventricle during diastole, leading to increased pressure in the left atrium.\r\n\r\nWhen auscultating the heart, a mid-diastolic murmur is heard as blood flows from the left atrium into the left ventricle through the narrowed mitral valve. The murmur is best heard at the apex of the heart, which corresponds to the point of maximal impulse (PMI).\r\n\r\nThis distinctive murmur is often described as a \"rumbling\" sound and is a hallmark of mitral stenosis. It occurs during the middle part of diastole, after the opening snap of the mitral valve.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 460.","responses":[{"text":"Tricuspid stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitral regurgitation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tricuspid regurgitation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic regurgitation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitral stenosis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":18785,"text":"Which of the following is the cause of early diastolic murmur audible at the 3rd left intercostal space?","explanation":"**Aortic regurgitation** is the cause of an early diastolic murmur audible at the 3rd left intercostal space. This murmur is due to the backflow of blood from the aorta into the left ventricle during diastole, following the closure of the aortic valve. The turbulence created by this retrograde flow generates the murmur, which is typically high-pitched and decrescendo in nature, meaning it starts loud and then decreases in volume. It is best heard at the left sternal border, particularly in the 3rd intercostal space, and is often accentuated when the patient is sitting up and leaning forward, as this position brings the heart closer to the chest wall.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 460.","responses":[{"text":"Tricuspid stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitral stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitral regurgitation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tricuspid regurgitation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic regurgitation","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":18789,"text":"Which of the following is the cause of the mid-systolic murmur heard at the 2nd right intercostal space?","explanation":"**Aortic stenosis** is the cause of the mid-systolic murmur heard at the 2nd right intercostal space. This murmur is typically due to the turbulent flow across a narrowed aortic valve. As the left ventricle contracts, it forces blood through the stenotic valve, creating a characteristic murmur that can be best heard in the aortic area, traditionally located in the 2nd right intercostal space near the sternum. Aortic stenosis is often recognized by its distinct sound, which can radiate to the neck and mimic the sound of carotid bruits.\r\n\r\nAortic regurgitation typically results in a diastolic murmur, not a systolic one. Pulmonary stenosis would produce a murmur heard best at the 2nd left intercostal space, not the right.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 460, 522.","responses":[{"text":"Mitral regurgitration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic regurgitation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tricuspid stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic stenosis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":18794,"text":"A 60-year-old, man with diabetes presents to the emergency room complaining of palpitation and suddenly collapses. Which of the following rhythms needs asynchronous direct cardio current\r\n(DCC)?","explanation":"**Ventricular fibrillation (VF)** is a life-threatening cardiac arrhythmia characterized by rapid, irregular, and chaotic electrical activity in the ventricles of the heart. During VF, the heart loses its ability to pump blood effectively, leading to a sudden loss of consciousness and pulselessness. It is a medical emergency that requires immediate intervention.\r\n\r\nAsynchronous direct current cardioversion (DCC), also known as defibrillation, is the treatment of choice for ventricular fibrillation. DCC involves delivering a synchronized electrical shock to the heart to reset its electrical activity and restore a normal rhythm. This shock is administered as soon as possible to stop the chaotic electrical patterns in the ventricles and allow the heart to regain an organized and coordinated rhythm.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 482.","responses":[{"text":"Atrial flutter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular fibrillation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrial fibrillation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrial tachycardia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular tachycardia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18795,"text":"A 54-year-old male presents to the outpatient department with a complaint of chest pain. He has history of hypertension and ischemic heart disease. His blood pressure is 140/90 mmHg, pulse is 70 beats/min, and regular. You add nitrates to his pharmacologic therapy. Which of the following drugs should not be used with nitrates?","explanation":"**Sildenafil** is a medication primarily used to treat erectile dysfunction (ED). It belongs to a class of drugs called phosphodiesterase type 5 (PDE-5) inhibitors. One of the  concerns with sildenafil is its potential interaction with nitrates, such as nitroglycerin, which are commonly used to relieve chest pain (angina) in patients with ischemic heart disease.\r\n\r\nWhen sildenafil is combined with nitrates, it can lead to a dangerous drop in blood pressure. Both drugs have vasodilatory effects, which means they relax blood vessels and can cause a significant reduction in blood pressure. This interaction can result in a condition called hypotension, which may lead to fainting, dizziness, or even a heart attack in individuals with underlying heart conditions.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 13th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2021: 107.","responses":[{"text":"Beta blocker","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antiplatelet drugs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcium channel blocker","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Angiotensin converting enzyme","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sildenafil","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":18815,"text":"Vascular injury is characterized by which of the following responses?","explanation":"When the vascular wall is injured, smooth muscle cells (SMCs) in the media, which are typically in a contractile state, transition to a **proliferative-synthetic phenotype.** This change enables them to migrate towards the intima, proliferate, and synthesize extracellular matrix components. This process plays a critical role in repairing the damaged vessel, but it can also contribute to pathologies such as atherosclerosis and restenosis after vascular interventions.\r\n\r\nThe response to vascular injury is complex and involves multiple factors, including the synthesis of extracellular matrix, not its reduction. Smooth muscle cell migration actually occurs from the media to the intima, not to the adventitia. Intimal thickening, rather than thinning, is a characteristic response to injury as smooth muscle cells and extracellular matrix accumulate in the intima. Lastly, vascular injury elicits a robust healing response, contrary to a reduced healing response.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 489.","responses":[{"text":"Intimal thinning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Smooth muscle cell migration from media to the adventitia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reduced healing response","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reduced synthesis of extracellular matrix","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shift from contractile to proliferative-synthetic phenotype of smooth muscle cells","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":18978,"text":"Which of the following statements is correct regarding aneurysms?","explanation":"**Atherosclerosis,** a condition characterized by the buildup of plaques in the arterial walls, weakens the vessel wall over time, making it more prone to dilation and **aneurysm formation.** This is especially true for aneurysms that occur in the aorta, the largest artery in the body, where the stress of blood pressure and the presence of atherosclerotic plaques can lead to the development of aneurysms, particularly abdominal aortic aneurysms.\r\n\r\nAneurysms can indeed occur in various locations within the vascular system, but they are most commonly found in the aorta, rather than the peripheral vasculature. Mycotic aneurysms, which are caused by an infection of the vessel wall, can be either true or false aneurysms depending on whether the infection involves all three layers of the arterial wall or just the outer layers. The morphology of aneurysms can provide clues to their etiology and natural history, but it is not a definitive indicator of pathogenesis as multiple factors can contribute to aneurysm formation. Lastly, in a false aneurysm (also known as a pseudoaneurysm), the hematoma that forms as a result of a vessel wall breach is contained by the surrounding tissue but maintains communication with the vascular space, which is a distinguishing feature from a true aneurysm.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2021: 511, 512.","responses":[{"text":"Aneurysms most commonly occur in the peripheral vasculature","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Morphology of the aneurysms is a good indicator of pathogenesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The hematoma within a false aneurysm does not communicate with the vascular space","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atherosclerosis is the most common cause of aneurysms","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mycotic aneurysms are always true aneurysms","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18982,"text":"Concerning ischemic heart diseases, which of the following statements is true?","explanation":"**Stable angina,** also known as angina pectoris, is characterized by chest pain or discomfort that occurs when there is a temporary imbalance between the oxygen demand and supply to the heart muscle. This imbalance is often caused by a fixed coronary artery lesion, such as atherosclerosis, which results in the narrowing of the coronary arteries. During periods of increased demand, such as physical exertion or stress, the narrowed artery cannot supply enough oxygen to meet the heart's needs, leading to angina symptoms.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 542, 543.","responses":[{"text":"Stable angina results from fixed coronary lesion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thrombus is a poor activator of growth-related signals in muscle cell","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Unstable angina is characterized by complete obstruction of the artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The death rate in the US from IHD has fallen by one-half since 1980","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vasoconstriction can result from increased release of NO","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18987,"text":"A 63-year-old woman with complains of a sudden onset of pain in the chest radiating to the back. She has a past history of poorly controlled hypertension.  On physical examination: heart rate. 90 beats/minute. respirations 20 /minute, temperature 36.8°C. and blood pressure 150/100 mm Hg. No murmurs are audible. A chest radiograph reveals a widened mediastinum. Laboratory findings: total serum creatine kinase of 55 U/L creatinine 0.9 mg/dL, and glucose 123 mg/dL. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Aortic dissection** is a medical emergency characterized by the tearing of the aortic wall, creating a false lumen within the aorta. Patients often present with severe chest pain that can radiate to the back, which is related to the involvement of the aortic arch and descending aorta. Hypertension is a common risk factor for aortic dissection, as it can lead to increased stress on the aortic wall.\r\n\r\nThe widened mediastinum on the chest radiograph is a classic finding in aortic dissection, resulting from the accumulation of blood in the false lumen.","reference":"Agabegi SS, Agabegi ED, Duncan MD, Chuang K. Step-Up to Medicine. 6th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2024: 53, 54.","responses":[{"text":"Infective endocarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myocardial infarction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dilated cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrinous pericarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic dissection","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":18989,"text":"A 49-year-old woman has poorly controlled atrial fibrillation. She suffers a 'stroke' and dies. In autopsy, her 600-gm heart is noted to have a mitral valve with partial fusion of the leaflets along with thickening and shortening of the chordae tendineae. There is an enlarged left atrium filled with mural thrombus. Which of the following underlying causes of death is she most likely to have?","explanation":"**Rheumatic heart disease** is a condition that can result from inadequately treated streptococcal infections, particularly in childhood. Over time, repeated episodes of these infections can lead to damage to the heart valves, especially the mitral valve. The characteristic findings of thickened and shortened chordae tendineae and fusion of mitral valve leaflets are indicative of chronic rheumatic heart disease.\r\n\r\nAtrial fibrillation is a common complication of mitral valve disease, further supporting the likelihood of rheumatic heart disease in this case. The presence of a mural thrombus in the left atrium is also consistent with atrial fibrillation, as it predisposes individuals to thromboembolic events such as strokes.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 562.","responses":[{"text":"Cardiac amyloidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coronary atherosclerosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rheumatic heart disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Marantic endocarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Systemic lupus erythematosus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":18994,"text":"Which of the following responses is true concerning myocardial ischemia?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 545, 547.","responses":[{"text":"Ischemia lasting more than 10 minutes results in irreversible injury","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coagulative necrosis is more important than apoptosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Loss of contractility occurs within 60 seconds","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"ATP is reduced to 50% normal in 30 minutes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Irreversible injury initially occurs immediately adjacent to the occluded coronary artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19215,"text":"Which of the following functions is not carried out by the endothelial cells?","explanation":"Endothelial cells, which line the inner surfaces of blood vessels, play essential roles in maintaining vascular homeostasis and participating in various physiological processes. However, the **formation of histamine** is primarily associated with mast cells and basophils rather than endothelial cells. Histamine is a biogenic amine that is released during allergic reactions and inflammation, contributing to vasodilation, increased vascular permeability, and the manifestation of allergy symptoms.","reference":"(1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 488.\r\n\r\n(2) Jiang, Hui, et al. “Mechanisms of Oxidized LDL-Mediated Endothelial Dysfunction and Its Consequences for the Development of Atherosclerosis.” Frontiers in Cardiovascular Medicine, 1 June 2022, https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fcvm.2022.925923/full.","responses":[{"text":"Oxidation of low density lipoprotein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Formation of interleukin 1, IL6, IL8","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Formation of von-Willebrand factor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Formation of collagen and proteoglycans","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Formation of histamine","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":19216,"text":"Which of the following is not a feature of an atheromatous plaque?","explanation":"**Lipid core within the media** is not a characteristic feature of an atheromatous plaque. Atheromatous plaques, the hallmark of atherosclerosis, predominantly affect the intima layer of arteries and not the media. These plaques are complex structures that involve the accumulation of lipids, primarily cholesterol and cholesterol esters, within the intimal layer of the artery, leading to the formation of a lipid core. This lipid core is characteristically surrounded by a fibrous cap composed of smooth muscle cells, collagen, and elastin.\r\n\r\nAtherosclerotic lesions are typically eccentric, forming protrusions into the lumen of the artery, rather than encircling the vessel uniformly. The preferential development of these plaques in certain regions, such as the greater involvement of the abdominal aorta compared to the thoracic aorta, reflects hemodynamic factors, vessel branching, and other localized influences.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 499, 501, 503.","responses":[{"text":"Greater involvement of the abdominal aorta than the thoracic aorta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eccentric lesions rather than circumferential lesions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lipid core within the media","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Covering fibrous cap","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intracellular and extracellular lipid deposits","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19217,"text":"A 45-year-old man is rushed to the hospital following the sudden onset of an episode of crushing substernal chest pain. He develops cardiogenic shock and receives advanced life support measures. An electrocardiogram (EKG) shows chances consistent with a large transmural anterolateral infarction involving the wall of the left ventricle. Which of the following microscopic findings is most likely to be present in this area 4 days following the onset of his chest pain?","explanation":"**Four days** after the onset of a myocardial infarction (heart attack), the affected area of the heart typically shows **myofiber necrosis with neutrophils.** During this phase, the necrotic cardiac myocytes are being removed by neutrophils, and there is an influx of inflammatory cells, primarily neutrophils, into the area of infarction. This is part of the acute inflammatory response to cell death.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nFibroblasts and collagen deposition occur later in the healing process, typically starting after the first week and continuing over several weeks as the necrotic tissue is replaced by scar tissue.\r\n\r\nCapillary proliferation and macrophages are seen in the subacute phase, usually after the first few days when macrophages replace neutrophils and begin to clear the necrotic tissue, and granulation tissue starts to form a week after infarction.\r\n \r\nPerivascular lymphocytic infiltrates and granulomatous inflammation are not typical features of the healing process in myocardial infarction.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 547, 549.","responses":[{"text":"Myofiber necrosis with neutrophils","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibroblasts and collagen deposition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Perivascular lymphocytic infiltrates","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Granulomatous inflammation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Capillary proliferation and macrophages","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19218,"text":"A 50-year-old man comes to the emergency department with\r\na sudden onset of substernal chest pain. The pain persists for the next three hours. He then becomes breathless and diaphoretic. On physical examination: temperature  37°C, pulse 100/minute, respiratory rate 26/minute, and blood pressure 130/90 mm Hg. A chest x-ray shows a slightly enlarged heart and mild pulmonary edema. An electrocardiogram (EKG) shows ST segment elevation in anterior leads V1-6. Which of the following serum laboratory test findings is most likely to be present in this man?","explanation":"Clinical presentation of substernal chest pain, breathlessness, diaphoresis, and ST segment elevation in anterior leads V1-6 on the electrocardiogram (EKG) strongly suggests an acute myocardial infarction (AMI) or heart attack. **Troponin** is a highly sensitive and specific marker for myocardial injury. Elevated levels of troponin in the blood are indicative of myocardial damage, which is a hallmark of AMI.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020:  550.","responses":[{"text":"Sodium of 115 mmol/L","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urea nitrogen of 110 mg/dL","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HDL cholesterol of 55 mg/dL","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alanine aminotransferase of 876 U/L","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Troponin of 32 ng/mL","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":19219,"text":"A 44-year-old woman dies as a consequence of a 'stroke'. At autopsy, she is found to have a large right basal ganglia hemorrhage. She has an enlarged 550 gm heart with predominantly left ventricular hypertrophy. Her kidneys are small, about 80 gm each, with cortical scarring, and microscopically they demonstrate small renal arterioles that have luminal narrowing from concentric intimal thickening. Which of the following is the most likely condition associated with her findings?","explanation":"The key pathological features that point towards **hypertensive emergency** in this case are the presence of a large right basal ganglia hemorrhage, an enlarged heart with predominantly left ventricular hypertrophy, and small kidneys with cortical scarring and microscopically demonstrated small renal arterioles with luminal narrowing from concentric intimal thickening.\r\n\r\nHypertensive emergency, also known as malignant hypertension, is characterized by severely elevated blood pressure that can lead to target organ damage. In this case, the brain hemorrhage, left ventricular hypertrophy, and renal changes are all consistent with the effects of chronic and severe hypertension on these organs.","reference":"(1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 490, 493. \r\n\r\n(2) Le T, Bhushan V, Qiu C, et al., eds. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2023. 33rd ed. McGraw Hill; 2023: 304.","responses":[{"text":"Monckeberg's sclerosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetes mellitus, type II","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertensive emergency","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypercholesterolemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19220,"text":"A 45-year-old man has had arthritis pain involving all extremities for the past 5 years. He has had worsening orthopnea and pedal edema for 6 months. There is no chest pain. On examination, he is afebrile. A chest radiograph shows cardiomegaly with prominent left and right heart borders, along with pulmonary edema. Laboratory studies show Na⁺ 139 mmol/L. K⁺ 4.3 mmol/L. CI- 99 mmol/L, CO2 25 mmol/L, urea nitrogen 18 mg/dL, creatinine 1.3 mg/dL, and glucose 200 mg/dL. Which of the following additional laboratory test findings is he most likely to have?","explanation":"The clinical presentation of this patient suggests congestive heart failure (CHF) with features of right-sided heart failure, such as pedal edema and hepatomegaly. In cases of chronic CHF, the liver often becomes congested, leading to **elevated serum ferritin levels.** Ferritin is a protein that stores iron in the body, and elevated levels can indicate iron overload, which can be seen in conditions like CHF.\r\n\r\nAnti-centromere antibodies are more related to autoimmune diseases like systemic sclerosis, an elevated erythrocyte sedimentation rate suggests inflammation, low hemoglobin with a low mean corpuscular volume (MCV) may indicate various types of anemia, and spherocytes are typically seen in hereditary spherocytosis or immune hemolytic anemias, which are unrelated to CHF.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 849.","responses":[{"text":"Hemoglobin of 10.7 g/dL with MCV of 72 fL","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Erythrocyte sedimentation rate of 79 mm/Hr","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anti-centromere antibody titer of 1:320","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spherocytes on his peripheral blood smear","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum ferritin of 800 ng/mL","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":19221,"text":"A 49-year-old man has a sudden onset of substernal chest pain with radiation to his left arm. This persists for the next 6 hours. He goes to the emergency department and on examination is afebrile. Laboratory studies show a serum cardiac troponin of 18 ng/mL. Angiography reveals a thrombosis of the anterior interventricular (left anterior descending) coronary artery. During the next 24 hours, which of the following is the most likely complication he will experience?","explanation":"The scenario described is consistent with an acute myocardial infarction (heart attack) due to the thrombosis of a coronary artery. In the aftermath of a myocardial infarction, various complications can arise, and **arrhythmias** are among the most common.\r\n\r\nArrhythmias can occur due to the damage to the cardiac tissue caused by the lack of blood flow during the infarction. In this case, the thrombosis of the anterior interventricular artery likely resulted in significant damage to the heart muscle. This can lead to electrical instability in the heart, resulting in arrhythmias such as ventricular fibrillation, ventricular tachycardia, or atrial fibrillation.\r\n\r\nArrhythmias following a myocardial infarction can be life-threatening and require prompt medical intervention. Therefore, close monitoring and appropriate management of arrhythmias are essential during the initial hours and days following a heart attack.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 551. \r\n\r\n(2)Le T, Bhushan V, Qiu C, et al., eds. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2023. 33rd ed. McGraw Hill; 2023: 314.","responses":[{"text":"Cardiac tamponade","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arrhythmia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Constrictive pericarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic necrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thromboembolism","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19222,"text":"A 78-year-old woman has had increasing dyspnea for the past 5 years. On examination, her blood pressure is 130/85 mm Hg. Her BMI is 35 kg/m2. Rales are auscultated in both lungs. Her B-type natriuretic peptide, C-reactive protein, and LDL cholesterol levels are elevated. A chest x-ray shows infiltrates in all lung fields and an enlarged heart. Echocardiography shows decreased ejection fraction with segmental wall motion abnormalities. Which of the following forms of cardiomyopathy is she most likely to have?","explanation":"**Ischemic cardiomyopathy** is typically caused by chronic coronary artery disease leading to repeated myocardial ischemia and infarctions, which can result in **heart failure**. The **decreased ejection fraction** and segmental wall motion abnormalities suggest myocardial damage, likely due to ischemia. The patient's age (78 years old), obesity (BMI of 35 kg/m^2), elevated C-reactive protein (CRP), and high LDL cholesterol levels are significant risk factors for coronary artery disease, which is the underlying cause of ischemic cardiomyopathy.\r\n\r\nHypertrophic cardiomyopathy is characterized by abnormal thickening of the heart muscle, particularly the interventricular septum.\r\n\r\nInfiltrative cardiomyopathy (e.g., amyloidosis) involves the deposition of abnormal substances in the heart tissue but is not typically associated with segmental wall motion abnormalities.\r\n\r\nArrhythmogenic cardiomyopathy primarily affects the right ventricle and is characterized by fatty or fibrofatty replacement of myocardium.\r\n\r\nAlcoholic cardiomyopathy is due to chronic alcohol abuse and typically presents with dilated cardiomyopathy, but the history provided does not indicate alcohol abuse.","reference":"Cabac‐Pogorevici I, Muk B, Rustamova Y, Kalogeropoulos A, Tzeis S, Vardas P. Ischaemic cardiomyopathy. Pathophysiological insights, diagnostic management and the roles of revascularisation and device treatment. Gaps and dilemmas in the era of advanced technology. European Journal of Heart Failure. Published May 2020. Accessed January 27, 2024. https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/ejhf.1747","responses":[{"text":"Ischemic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Alcoholic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arrhythmogenic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infiltrative","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertrophic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19231,"text":"Which of the following drugs depresses the automaticity of the SA node as well as ectopic foci, abbreviates the action potential duration of Purkinje fibers, and slows A-V conduction?","explanation":"**Lignocaine (Lidocaine)** remarkably depresses the automaticity of the SA node as well as ectopic foci, which are common sources of arrhythmias. Additionally, lignocaine abbreviates the action potential duration of Purkinje fibers. This abbreviation is particularly important as it affects the refractory period and the rhythm of heartbeat, contributing to its antiarrhythmic effects.\r\n\r\nMoreover, Lignocaine also plays a role in slowing AV conduction. This slowing down is beneficial in preventing the rapid transmission of irregular electrical signals from the atria to the ventricles, which can lead to an irregular and often rapid heart rate. Its selective effect on ischemic or depolarized Purkinje and ventricular tissues, while sparing normal cardiac tissue, makes Lignocaine a drug of choice in acute settings, especially during myocardial infarction or during surgical procedures where the heart might be at risk of ischemic episodes.","reference":"(1)Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 13th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2021: 126. \r\n\r\n(2) Davis CW. USMLE® Step 1 Lecture Notes 2019: Pharmacology. Kaplan Medical; 2019: 107.","responses":[{"text":"Lignocaine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Procainamide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Quinidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bretylium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Propranolol","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19242,"text":"Which of the following drugs has been demonstrated, to retard the progression of left ventricular dysfunction \u0026 prolong survival of congestive heart failure patients?","explanation":"**Enalapril** belongs to a class of medications known as angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) inhibitors. In congestive heart failure (CHF), the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system (RAAS) plays a crucial role in exacerbating the condition. ACE inhibitors like enalapril block the conversion of angiotensin I to angiotensin II, a potent vasoconstrictor, and also reduce aldosterone secretion. By inhibiting these pathways, enalapril dilates blood vessels, reduces preload and afterload, and decreases the workload on the heart. Enalapril has the ability to improve cardiac function, reduce symptoms of heart failure, and, most importantly, prolong the survival of patients with congestive heart failure.","reference":"(1) Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 13th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2021: 120. \r\n\r\n(2) Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 236.","responses":[{"text":"Furosemide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amlodipine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enalapril","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Amrinone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Digoxin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19263,"text":"Which of the following is the most significant feature of the antiarrhythmic action of lignocaine?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 252.","responses":[{"text":"Shortening of action potential duration","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Prolongation of effective refractory period","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Suppression of phase-4 depolarization in ventricular ectopic foci","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prolongation of action potential duration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Depression of membrane responsiveness","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19264,"text":"Aging is a natural process with physiological changes, many of them are merely a decline in the rate of functioning. After what age does a reduction in the metabolic rate of about 7% occur every 10 years?","explanation":"Around the age of 30, individuals may start to notice a subtle decrease in their metabolic rate. This reduction becomes more noticeable as they progress into their 40s, 50s, and beyond.","reference":"Ilyas M. Public Health and Community Medicine. 7th ed. Time Publishers; 2006: 513.","responses":[{"text":"50 years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"20 years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"30 years","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"60 years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"40 years","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19265,"text":"Cancer arises from the transformation of normal cells into tumor cells in a multi-stage process that generally progresses from a precancerous lesion to a malignant tumor. These changes are the result of the interaction between a person's genetic factors and three categories of external agents. Considering the external agents, which of the following can be classified as a physical carcinogen?","explanation":"**Ionizing radiation** includes high-energy radiation such as X-rays and gamma rays. Exposure to ionizing radiation can damage the DNA within cells, leading to mutations and disruptions in the normal control of cell division. These genetic changes can increase the risk of cancer development.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides, Community Medicine, \"Cancer Epidemiology, Risk Factors, and Prevention\".","responses":[{"text":"Human papillomavirus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aflatoxin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ionizing radiation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Asbestos","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arsenic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19266,"text":"A 45-year-old man visits a doctor for his concern regarding his risk of heart disease. He explains that his father died of a heart attack at the age of 52 years. He seeks advice on diet. The doctor advises cutting down on the use of certain fats. Which one of the following options illustrates the most important food group to be avoided by the person?","explanation":"**Trans fats** are artificial fats created through a process called hydrogenation, often used in processed and fried foods to extend their shelf life and enhance texture. \r\n\r\nTrans fats have been shown to significantly increase the levels of low-density lipoprotein cholesterol (LDL-C), also known as \"bad cholesterol,\" while simultaneously lowering high-density lipoprotein cholesterol (HDL-C), or \"good cholesterol.\" Elevated levels of LDL-C and reduced HDL-C are well-established risk factors for coronary heart disease.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides, Community medicine \" Lifestyle modification for prevention of Cardiovascular Disease\".","responses":[{"text":"Polyunsaturated fat","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trans fat","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Omega 6 fat","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Monounsaturated fat","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Saturated fat","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19269,"text":"A 10-year-old boy is brought to the outpatient department with complaints of high-grade fever for the past 10 days. He also has pain in his right shoulder and right knee. For the past 2 days, he has been experiencing orthopnea. On auscultation, pansystolic murmur is heard. He had a history of upper respiratory tract infection 3 weeks back. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Rheumatic fever** is a systemic disease that can occur after an infection with group A Streptococcus, typically manifesting 2-3 weeks after a streptococcal pharyngitis or 'strep throat'.\r\n\r\nThe symptoms described, including the migratory polyarthritis (joint pain), carditis (evidenced by the pansystolic murmur and orthopnea indicating heart involvement), and a preceding streptococcal infection, align with the major criteria of the Jones criteria used in the diagnosis of rheumatic fever.\r\n \r\nRheumatic heart disease is a complication that can arise from recurrent or severe rheumatic fever and would be suggested by evidence of chronic valve disease, not typically apparent so acutely after the infection. Ventricular septal defect is a congenital condition and wouldn't explain the acute presentation and recent infection. Infective endocarditis could present with fever and heart murmur, but the joint involvement and the recent streptococcal infection make rheumatic fever more likely. Enteric fever (typhoid) could cause prolonged fever but would not typically present with the joint pains or the heart findings described here.","reference":"Khan PA. Basis of Pediatrics. 10th ed. Paramount Books (Pvt.) Ltd; 2018: 226.","responses":[{"text":"Rheumatic heart disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rheumatic fever","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Infective endocarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enteric fever","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19280,"text":"A 50-year-old male with chronic hypertension and dilated cardiomyopathy is admitted with chest pain of 4 hours. His electrocardiogram (EKG) shows ST-segment elevation in the chest leads. On angiography, which artery is most likely to be blocked?","explanation":"ST-segment elevation on the EKG, particularly in the chest leads, is a strong indicator of an acute myocardial infarction (MI), often referred to as a heart attack. The specific location of the ST-segment elevation can provide clues about which coronary artery is affected.\r\n\r\nThe **left anterior descending** artery (LAD) artery is commonly known as the \"widow-maker\" because a blockage in this artery can lead to a significant portion of the left ventricle being deprived of oxygenated blood supply. This can result in a large, anterior wall myocardial infarction, which is associated with a high risk of complications and mortality.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 445, 449.","responses":[{"text":"LAD","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"LCX","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"RCA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"OMI","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"PDA","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19291,"text":"A 25-year-old female presents to the outpatient department with a complaint of shortness of breath. Her blood pressure is 110/70 mm of Hg, pulse is 110 per min regular. Cardiovascular examination reveals pansystolic murmur of grade\r\nlll that increases on expiration. What would be the most likely clinical diagnosis?","explanation":"**Mitral regurgitation** is a valvular heart disorder characterized by the improper closure of the mitral valve during systole, allowing the backflow of blood from the left ventricle into the left atrium. The pansystolic murmur heard during auscultation is a classic hallmark of this condition. The grade III murmur intensity and the increase in murmur during expiration are indicative of significant regurgitation through the mitral valve.\r\n\r\nPatients with mitral regurgitation often present with symptoms like shortness of breath due to the inefficient forward flow of blood from the left ventricle into the systemic circulation, leading to volume overload of the left atrium and pulmonary congestion.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2019: 81.","responses":[{"text":"Pulmonary stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tricuspid regurgitation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitral regurgitation","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":19292,"text":"A 45-year-old current smoker presents to the outpatient department with the complaint of pain in calf muscles during walking relieved by rest. His blood pressure is 120/80 mm Hg. Pulse is 70 beats per minute and regular. His baseline investigations are normal, but his lipid profile is deranged. Which type of cholesterol is good for health?","explanation":"**HDL (High-Density Lipoprotein)** is often referred to as \"good cholesterol\" because of its beneficial role in the body. It functions by transporting cholesterol from various tissues and blood vessels back to the liver for elimination. This process is known as reverse cholesterol transport and helps to reduce the accumulation of cholesterol in the arteries, which is a risk factor for atherosclerosis and cardiovascular diseases.\r\n\r\nHaving higher levels of HDL in the blood is associated with a lower risk of heart disease. In contrast, elevated levels of LDL-C (Low-Density Lipoprotein Cholesterol), often termed \"bad cholesterol,\" are associated with an increased risk of atherosclerosis and cardiovascular events.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 496.","responses":[{"text":"Total cholesterol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HDL","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Triglycerides","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Non-HDL","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"LDL-C","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19296,"text":"In aortic regurgitation, systolic blood pressure in the lower limbs,\r\n20 mm Hg higher than the upper limbs is noted in which of the following signs?","explanation":"**Hill's sign** is an important clinical finding associated with aortic regurgitation, a condition where the aortic valve fails to close properly, leading to the backflow of blood from the aorta into the left ventricle during diastole. As a result, the left ventricle becomes volume overloaded, leading to increased stroke volume and elevated systolic blood pressure in the upper extremities.\r\n\r\nTo detect Hill's sign, blood pressure measurements are typically taken simultaneously in both the upper and lower limbs. The significant difference of 20 mm Hg or more in systolic blood pressure between the upper and lower limbs is considered a positive Hill's sign and strongly suggests the presence of aortic regurgitation.","reference":"Dewaswala N, Chait R. Aortic Regurgitation. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK555944/","responses":[{"text":"Traube's sign","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Demuset sign","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hill's sign","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pistol shot","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Quincke's sign","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19297,"text":"Left ventricular hypertrophy is diagnosed with what value of SV1+RV5 according to voltage criteria?","explanation":"**Left ventricular hypertrophy (LVH)** is diagnosed using voltage criteria, and one of the commonly used criteria is the Sokolow-Lyon criteria, which includes the measurement of SV1+RV5 on an electrocardiogram (ECG). According to these criteria, a value of **35 mm or more** for SV1+RV5 is indicative of LVH.\r\n\r\nIn the Sokolow-Lyon criteria, SV1 represents the highest amplitude of the S wave in lead V1, and RV5 represents the highest amplitude of the R wave in lead V5. When the sum of these two values exceeds or equals 35 mm, it suggests the presence of left ventricular hypertrophy.\r\n\r\nLVH is a condition characterized by the thickening of the walls of the left ventricle of the heart, often in response to chronic high blood pressure or other cardiac conditions.","reference":"Antikainen, R. L., et al. “Left Ventricular Hypertrophy by Sokolow-Lyon Voltage Criterion Predicts Mortality in Overweight Hypertensive Subjects.” Journal of Human Hypertension, Jan. 2009, https://www.nature.com/articles/jhh2008102.","responses":[{"text":"35 mm","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"28 mm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"26 mm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"25 mm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"30 mm","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":19298,"text":"A 47-year-old man with history of hypertesnion presents to the emergency room with the complaint of severe sub-sternal chest pain on mild exertion since morning. His electrocardiogram (ECG) shows ST elevation in chest leads. He is treated for an acute anterior wall myocardial infarction. What is the recommended dose of aspirin to support primary percutaneous coronary intervention?","explanation":"Aspirin, also known as acetylsalicylic acid, is a crucial medication in the management of acute coronary syndromes, including MI. It exerts its effects by inhibiting platelet aggregation, thereby reducing the risk of thrombotic events in the coronary arteries.\r\n\r\nFor patients undergoing primary PCI for acute MI, the recommended dose of aspirin is generally in the range of **162 to 325 mg**, taken orally as soon as possible after the diagnosis is made. This dose is effective in preventing further clot formation and improving coronary blood flow during the procedure.","reference":"Lawton, Jennifer S., et al. “2021 ACC/AHA/SCAI Guideline for Coronary Artery Revascularization: A Report of the American College of Cardiology/American Heart Association Joint Committee on Clinical Practice Guidelines.” Circulation, 18 Jan. 2022, https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/10.1161/CIR.0000000000001038.","responses":[{"text":"100 mg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"200 to 350 mg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"200 to 400 mg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"500 to 600 mg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"162 to 325 mg","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21738,"text":"A patient who is a known case of asthma, presented with symptoms of stable angina. Which of the following will be the preferred treatment in this case?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6523058/\r\n(2) Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine, 24th edition, page 500","responses":[{"text":"Nitrates","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitrates and beta-blockers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcium channel blocker","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Beta-blockers and calcium channel blockers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diuretics","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22385,"text":"Which type of shock has warm peripheries as one of its clinical signs?","explanation":null,"reference":"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470316/","responses":[{"text":"Hypotensive shock","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anaphylactic shock","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Distributive shock","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Neurogenic shock","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiogenic shock","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22520,"text":"An electrocardiogram of a patient shows broad complex tachycardia. The man was previously diagnosed with ischemic heart disease. He now presents with dyspnea followed by syncope, with a blood pressure of 60/50. What is the most appropriate treatment in this case?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) https://www.escardio.org/static-file/Escardio/Guidelines/publications/SVAguidelines-SVA-ES.pdf\r\n(2) Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine, 24th edition page 475.","responses":[{"text":"Beta blocker","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amiodarone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Quinidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IV amiodarone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"DC cardioversion","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22521,"text":"A pregnant woman presents to the outpatient department with complaints of shortness of breath. On precordial examination, a mid-diastolic murmur is heard. Which of the following could be the underlying cause of this murmur?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine, 24th edition, page 460.","responses":[{"text":"Systemic hypertension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitral regurgitation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic regurgitation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitral stenosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22836,"text":"A patient was admitted to the hospital for an anterior wall myocardial infarction. On 3rd day after treatment, he developed chest pain and shortness of breath. An immediate ECG shows concave ST-elevations in all leads except lead II. Which of the following could be the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1)Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine, 24th edition, page 496.\r\n(2)https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9683083/#:~:text=The%20physical%20sign%20of%20acute,segment%20depression%20are%20common%20E.C.G.","responses":[{"text":"Mitral regurgitation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sinus Bradycardia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reinfarction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inter-ventricular Septal Rupture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Post-Myocardial pericarditis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22837,"text":"Which of the following is the most common cause of sudden cardiac death after an acute myocardial infarction?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine, 24th edition, page 495.","responses":[{"text":"Ventricular fibrillations","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular aneurysm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Papillary muscle rupture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pericarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Recurrent angina","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22838,"text":"Which of the following is a common cause of pansystolic murmur after an episode of acute myocardial infarction?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine, 24th edition, page 496.","responses":[{"text":"Dressler’s syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular aneurysm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitral regurgitation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular arrhythmias","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Post-MI pericarditis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22839,"text":"Which of the following is the correct criteria for definitive infective endocarditis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine, 24th edition, page 529","responses":[{"text":"two minor and four minor criteria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"one major criteria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"one major and one minor criteria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"two major criteria","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"two major and five minor","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":23133,"text":"A 60-year-old man presents to the emergency with a blood pressure of 80/60 and chest pain with dizziness. His ECG shows wide and bizarre QRS complexes. What is the best treatment option for this patient?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine, 24th edition, page 475","responses":[{"text":"Beta blockers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IV amiodarone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcium channel blockers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lidocaine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"DC cardioversion","correct":true,"visible":false}]}
]

